{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"73ca19ac-f964-4f29-a6db-16314533b589","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_fLjWfFwoICyP2LHqOo4FVK","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Configuring NativeAOT crash dumps"},"type":"function"}],"interactionId":"992c1ee2-e776-49af-bc49-7c993e9a990c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app running in Kubernetes. They have `createdump` at `/opt/tools/createdump`. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. For .NET NativeAOT apps, crash dump collection works differently than regular CoreCLR apps. The environment variables needed are:\n   - `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` - enables automatic dump collection on crash\n   - `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` - full dump (or other types: 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n   - `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` - path/pattern for dump files\n   - `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` - points to the createdump tool location, which is critical since theirs is at `/opt/tools/createdump`\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically in .NET 8+, crash dump generation is supported, though I need to verify the exact variable names since NativeAOT has some differences from the standard runtime.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the Kubernetes setup requirements: I'll need a writable volume for the dump files, the `SYS_PTRACE` capability so createdump can attach to the crashing process, and appropriate resource limits to prevent the dumps from consuming too much space. Now I'm putting together the full pod specification with a volume for storing the dumps and configuring the security context to grant the necessary ptrace capability—createdump should already be available at the specified path, so no sidecar is needed.","outputTokens":850,"requestId":"502D:2C454F:24717D:2DFA44:69F55450"},"id":"f3483ed8-50bb-4cce-9b23-b5eee9fcef6d","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:33:21.262Z","parentId":"022408ff-d6cf-46c2-a023-20f195a9f045"}
